[[Colonel]] '''James L. Pohl''' is an [[United States|American]] [[lawyer]] and an officer in the [[United States Army]].<ref name=DoDJudgesBiosJamesLPohl>
{{cite web
| url=http://media.miamiherald.com/smedia/2008/04/02/10/judgesbios.source.prod_affiliate.56.pdf
| title=Col., James L. Pohl, US Army
| page='''page 9'''
| publisher=[[United States Air Force]]
| accessdate=2008-06-19
| quote=
}}
[http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmedia.miamiherald.com%2Fsmedia%2F2008%2F04%2F02%2F10%2Fjudgesbios.source.prod_affiliate.56.pdf&date=2008-06-19 mirror]
</ref>

He is notable for having been appointed as a judge on a [[Guantanamo military commission]].<ref name=DoDJudgesBiosJamesLPohl/>
He is Presiding over the Commission of [[Ahmed Darbi]] and [[Abd el-Rahim al-Nashiri]].<ref name=IdahoStatesman2009-01-05>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.idahostatesman.com/1425/story/623260.html
| title=New Guantanamo chief judge warns of change with Obama
| publisher=[[Idaho Statesman]]
| author=[[Carol Rosenberg]]
| date=2009-01-05
| accessdate=2009-01-06
| quote=
}} [http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.idahostatesman.com%2F1425%2Fstory%2F623260.html&date=2009-01-06 mirror]
</ref>
He is notable for serving as the judge of several of the GIs in the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse]] cases, and barring the demolition of [[Abu Ghraib]] because he had ruled it a crime scene.

On 6 January 2009 Pohl was appointed to replace [[Ralph Kohlmann]] as the Chief Presiding Officer for the Military Commissions.<ref name=IdahoStatesman2009-01-05/>

Pohl received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Pepperdine University]] in 1978.<ref name="IdahoStatesman2009-01-05"/>

==Suspension of Guantanamo Hearings==
On January 29, 2009, Pohl denied the request of the [[Obama Administration]] to delay proceeding for 120 days in the case of [[Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri]].<ref name=TheGuardian2009-01-30>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/jan/30/guantanamo-closure-uss-cole-obama
| title=Former commander of attacked US war ship slams Obama over Guant<U+00E1>namo
| publisher=[[The Guardian]]
| author=
| date=2009-01-30
| accessdate=2009-01-30
| quote=
| location=London
| first=McClatchy
| last=Newspapers
}} 
</ref> 
Pohl argued that tribunal rules give the judges sole authority to delay cases and that postponing proceedings against [[Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri]] was not reasonable and "does not serve the interest of justice".<ref name=WashingtonPost2009-01-29>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/29/AR2009012902021_pf.html
| title=Military Judge Denies Obama Request to Suspend Guantanamo Hearings
| publisher=[[Washington Post]]
| author=Peter Finn
| date=2009-01-29
| accessdate=2009-01-29
| quote=
}} 
</ref> 
According to [[Carol Rosenberg]], writing in the ''[[Miami Herald]]'', Pohl's ruling stated:<ref name=MiamiHerald2009-01-29>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.miamiherald.com/1218/story/879325.html
| title=Guant<U+00E1>namo judge defies Obama's order for freeze
| publisher=[[Miami Herald]]
| author=Carol Rosenberg
| date=2009-01-29
| accessdate=2008-09-28
