</ref>

On February 5, 2009, the charges were dismissed without prejudice by the convening authority.<ref>http://www.reuters.com/article/newsMaps/idUSTRE5150IL20090206</ref>

==Assigned to investigate the Fort Hood shootings==

Pohl was assigned to serve as the investigating officer for the [[article 32 hearing]] for [[Major (rank)|Major]] [[Nidal Malik Hasan]], the suspect in the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]].<ref name=SanAntonio2010-02-13>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/84314202.html
| title=Hearing date for Hasan delayed
| publisher=[[San Antonio Express]]
| date=2010-02-13
| author=Valentino Lucio
| accessdate=2010-02-13
| quote=Col. James Pohl, the investigative officer assigned to the case, granted a request from the defense to delay the start of the hearing, which was originally set for March 1. Pohl served on a Guantanamo military commission and oversaw the case of U.S. troops charged in the Abu Ghraib prison scandal.
}}</ref>

==Assigned to Brigadier General Sinclair Court-Martial==

Pohl was assigned to preside over the court martial of [[Brigadier General]]
[[Jeffrey A. Sinclair]], a former deputy commander of the [[82nd Airborne Division]], charged with [[sodomy]].<ref name=FayOb2013-01-21>
{{cite news 
| url         = http://www.fayobserver.com/articles/2013/01/21/1228945?sac=fo.military
| title       = Experienced military judge draws assignment for Brig. Gen, Jeffrey Sinclair's hearing
| publisher   = [[Fayatsville Observer]]
| author      = Drew Brooks
| date        = 2013-01-21
| archivedate = 2013-02-15
| archiveurl  = http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fayobserver.com%2Farticles%2F2013%2F01%2F21%2F1228945%3Fsac%3Dfo.military&date=2013-02-15
| deadurl     = No 
| quote       = Pohl is believed to be the most senior of all of the Army's judges, with a career that spans four decades. Observers call him a fair judge who isn't afraid to hold lawyers to task.
}}
</ref>  Following acceptance of Sinclair's guilty pleas on some (but not all) of the charges he faced (including adultery with three different women, violating a general order by possessing pornography in the Afghan theater of operations, and conduct unbecoming an officer), Pohl sentenced Sinclair to a reprimand and forfeiture of five thousand dollars a month for four months ($20,000.00 total).

